      "text": "Paphos Archaeological Park is one of Cyprus’s most important historical and cultural treasures. Recognized as a UNESCO World Heritage Site, the park is located near the Paphos harbor and offers a rich collection of ruins dating from prehistoric times to the Middle Ages. The site is particularly famous for its remarkably well-preserved Roman mosaics found in the Houses of Dionysos, Theseus, Aion, and Orpheus. These mosaics depict mythological scenes and everyday life with extraordinary artistic detail, making them some of the finest in the Mediterranean.In addition to the mosaics, visitors can explore ancient villas, a Roman amphitheater, a lighthouse, early Christian basilicas, and the impressive Tombs of the Kings carved into the rock. These underground tombs were used by high-ranking officials during the Hellenistic and Roman periods. With clearly marked walking paths and informative signage, the park offers a captivating journey through centuries of Cypriot history. Whether you're a history enthusiast or a casual traveler, the Paphos Archaeological Park provides an unforgettable experience that connects you to the ancient world."
